    <!-- Main Content -->
    <div class="container content">
        <h1 class="display-4">Welcome to Banker's Algorithm Simulator</h1>
        <p>The Banker's Algorithm is a resource allocation and deadlock avoidance algorithm developed by Edsger Dijkstra. It tests for safety by simulating the allocation of predetermined maximum possible amounts of all resources and then makes a decision whether it is safe to allocate resources to processes or not.</p>

        <div class="row">
            <!-- Advantages Section -->
            <div class="col-md-6 advantages">
                <h2>Advantages</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>It contains various resources that meet the requirements of each process.</li>
                    <li>Each process provides information to the OS for upcoming resource requests, resource numbers, and how long they will be held.</li>
                    <li>It helps the OS manage and control process requests for each type of resource in the system.</li>
                    <li>It has a Max resource attribute that indicates the maximum number of resources each process can hold in a system.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Disadvantages Section -->
            <div class="col-md-6 disadvantages">
                <h2>Disadvantages</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>It requires a fixed number of processes, and no additional processes can be started while the algorithm is in execution.</li>
                    <li>The algorithm does not allow processes to change their maximum needs while processing tasks.</li>
                    <li>Each process must know and state its maximum resource requirements in advance.</li>
                    <li>While resource requests are granted in a finite time, the limit for resource allocation is one year.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

